The most direct contradiction is between the testimonies of Fairplay (Testimony 0: "There was blood on both hands of the assailant. I sincerely and distinctly remember that!") and the evidence regarding the Defendant's Leather Gloves (Evidence 3: "The leather gloves the defendant was wearing at the time of the incident. There is a bloodstain on the right glove.").

If the defendant truly had blood "on both hands," then both gloves would be bloodstained, but the evidence records only one glove stained (the right glove). This means Fairplay's testimony is contradicted by the physical evidence.

